{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930122401/0815.xml":{"full_text":"GREEN FIGURES\nFOUR MILLION\nARE IOLE\nDecrease In Percentage of\nUnion Unemployed Shown\nIn New Reports, He Says\nBy Universal Service\nAlthough unemployment increas\ned in the first two weeks of De\neember, the Increase in trade\nunions was less than is usual at\nthis tipie of year, according to re\nports made public last night by\nb William Green, president of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nIncrease For November\nHe said:\n\u201cUnemployment in the first\nweeks of December increased as\nit usually does at this season\nand more are now out of work\n\u2022than at any time during the\npresent depression. Our prelimi\nnary estimate of the total num\nber unemployed in the United\nStates in December, based on\nGovernment employment figures,\nsupplemented by our own, is 5,-\n300,000. According to our re\nvised estimate for November 5,-\n000,000 were out of work in that\nmonth, showing an increase of\n300,000 from November to De\ncember.\nSuffering Intense\n\u201cSuffering from unemploy\nment is already intense and\nevery effort is needed to relieve\nthe unemployed. Many Amerl-\ncan citizens in the last month\nhave shown the same spirit in\nmeeting this emergency which\ncarried us through the problems\nof war 13 years ago. Only the\nsame self-sacrificing effort can\nhelp us to meet the present\ngreat human emergency. Con\n.tributicgis for relief of the unem-\nployed and efforts to provide\nwork must continue even more\nvigorously through the next two\nmonths. We cannot hope for\nany general improvement before\nMarch.\nPercentage Drops\n\u201cIn spite of the tragedy of\nmore than 5,000,000 out of work,\nour figures for December give\nground for encouragement. Un\nemployment did not increase as\nmuch from November to Decem\nber this year as it usually does\neven in normal years. In 1928\nthe increase in the number of\nunion members out of work was\n17 per cent from November to\nDecember; in 1929, 28 per cent,\nwhile this year the increase was\nonly 5 per cent. This indica\nk tion that the rising trend of un-\nemployment is slackening is en\ncouraging news, indeed. If Jan\nuary figures again show less\nthan the normal increase, we\nwill be justified in the belief\nthat a change for the better may\nbe in the making. Better em\nployment and increased buying\npower of wage-earners is fund*-\nmental to business revival.\u201d\nWoman Is Elected\n1 Member of Sigma Xi\nBWTHT.FHBM. Pa., Dec. 24.\u2014For\nthe first time in the history of\nthe chapter of Sigma Xi, the na\ntional engineering research fra\nternity, at Lehigh University, a\nwoman has been elected to mem\nbership.\nShe is Selma F. Hermann, an\nengineering foundation research\nfellow at Lehigh. Seven other re\nsearch workers have been elected\nto membership as well as seven\nmembers of the faculty and six\nundergraduates.\n[Fan Alen Daughter\nEngaged to Prince\nNEW YORK, Dec. 24 (U.S.).\nDispatches from Paris today re\nported the engagement of Miss\nLouise Astor Van Alen, beautiful\ndaughter of one of the richest\nand most exclusive families of\nthis country, and Prince Alexis\nMdivani, descendant of Georgian\nnobility.\nChristmas Eve\nGala Program\nGlorious Christmas Music by the Camel Orchestra... Reinaid\nWerrenrath\u2019s magnificent baritone blending with the rich voices\nof the Camel Glee Club Mary McCoy, Willard Robison,\nthe Camel Quartet all the best loved stars of the\nCamel\nPLEASURE \u2018SSamBBt\nHOUR\n9.30 to 10.30 Eastern Time\n&30 to 930 Central Time\nWetineadng Evening\non the N. B. C. Network\u2014wjz\nAnd Associated Stations\nBirths, Deaths and Marriages\nALICE MAY CLAYTON\nFuneral services for Miss Alice\nMay Clayton, retired teacher and\nformer administrative principal\nof the Beaton-Blake Schools, who\ndied Sunday following a brief\nillness, were held yesterday at\nthe undertaking establishment of\nJohn R. Wright, with burial in\nCongressional Cemetery.\nMiss Clayton, who was retired\nlast year, had been connected\nwith the public schools for 44\nyears prior. She began her career\nat the Peabody School. In 1921\nshe was made principal of the\nnew John Burroughs School and\nfive years after, she was trans\nferred to the Seaton School.\nWhen that school was combined\nwith the Blake, she was made\nadministrative principal of both.\nSurviving her are two brothers,\nDr. Benjamin Clayton and Charles\nClayton, both of Washington,\nand two sisters, Mrs. R. A. San\nders, of this city, and Mrs.\nFrank Dorian, of New York.\nS. EARLE EVERHAM\nS. Earle Everham, 46, employe\nof th/Hecht Company, died yes\nterday at his home, 2224 Min\nnesota Ave. S. E., from injuries\nreceived Saturday in an automo\nbile accident-\nA resident of Washington for\nthe past 12 years, Mr. Everham\ncame here from Philadelphia\nwhere he had lived for the great\ner part of his life.\nSurviving him are his widow,\nMrs. Anna H. Everham; two step\nchildren, Mrs. Dorothy Seaton and\nMrs. Elizabeth Munday, both of\nWashington; a brother, Harry\nEverham, of Philadelphia, and\ntwo sisters, Mrs. Harty Weaver,\nof Philadelphia, and Mrs. May\nGordon, of Newpdrt, R. I.\nFuneral services will probably\nbe held on Friday from William\nJ. Nalley\u2019s, 522 Eighth St. S. E.,\nwhere the body is now resting,\nwith burial in Cedar Hill Ceme\ntery-\nMRS. SARAH ELLEN DeSHAZO\nFuiferal services for Mrs. Sarah\nEllen DeShazo, 62, Ot Silver\nSpring, Md., who died yesterday\nfollowing a brief illness, will be\nheld on Friday from the parlors\nof James T. Ryan, 317 Pennsyl\nvania Ave. S. E. Mass will be\nsaid at the Holy Comforter\nChurch at 10 o\u2019clock and burial\nwill follow in Congressional Ceme\ntery.\nMrs. DeShazo, who had lived in\nSilver Spring for a number of\nyears, is survived by a daughter\nand two\nCRITTENDON H. WALKER\nFuneral services for Crittendon\nH. Walker, 73, former delegate to\nthe Maryland State legislature,\nwho died Monday at his home in\nGaithersburg, Md., held\nlate today at his home, with burial\nfollowing in Forest Oak Cemetery,\nGaithersburg.\nMr. Walker, who was a delegate\nfor two terms to the State legisla\nture, was also a Montgomery\ncounty commissioner for two\nterms. He is survived by his\nwidow, two sons, Walter Cook and\nCrittendon H., Jr.; a daughter,\nMrs. Virginia Plummer; three\nbrothers, James K., Thomas and\nMcKendra Walker, and a sister,\nMrs. Cornelius Browning, of Ger\nmantown, Pa.\nLIEUT. L. B. McENTYRE\nThe body of Lieut. Lawrence\nB. McEntyre, U. S. Army, is to\nday en route from Tonawanda,\nN. Y., for burial on Friday in\nArlington National Cemetery.\nFuneral services will be held at\n1 o\u2019clock on Friday at St. Paul\u2019s\nChurch, Rock Creek parish.\nLieutenant McEntyre, who died\non Sunday, is survived by his\nwife, Mrs. Julia A. McEntyre.\nBIRTHS\nWilliam J. and Helen C. Hudson, girl.\nWilliam C. and Viola Cumberland,\nboy.\nCarl A. and Josephine Krorman, boy.\nFrederick and Nellie Davis, boy.\nMaurice D. and Dorothy Aaronsen.\nboy.\nJohn W. and Lydia Glrvin, srirl.\nHobson R. and Mae Jackson, girl.\nArthur and Margaret Logan, boy.\nJoseph E. and Evelyn Jackson, boy.\nSaunders and Willie Thornton, boy.\nArthur and Ada Sharp, girl.\nTHS WASHINGTON hmm\nDEATHS\nEHRHART, WILLIAM C.\u2014-PMeedawy\non Wedneeday morning, December 24.\ni\u00bb jssft fcJKrFffiWr,,*\nBeeidea hie wife he io survived by four\nElmlSa E Ul \u00dfrown\u201cAdeeis.*Jttrhirt, and\n\u201c\"yunenU^aanricee' conducted from\n&V C\u00bbT w\nCemetery.\nRobey), of SIB Third Street Southeast.\nFuneral services will be conducted from\nhis late residence. 818 Third St. Southeast,\non Friday morning. December 26. 1030. at\n6:30 o'clock, thence to Bt. Teresa\u2019s Catho\nlic Church, where requiem mass will be\nsaid at 0 o'clock for the repose of his\neoul. Relatives and friends an invited\nto attend. Interment will follow at\nQgon HiU, Md.\nGOODWIN, MADGE Passed away on\nWednesday morning, December 24, 1030,\nMADGE GOODWIN. _\nRemains resting at the W. W. Cham\nbers Company funeral home, 1400 Chapin\nSt. N. W.\nNotice of funeral services hereafter.\nFUNERAL DIKKCTOKb a\nBigger and Better Funerals\nAt Half the Usual Cost Are Dons by\nCHAMBERS\nA Whole Funeral for as\nFLORISTS\nAPPROPRIATE Funera. Tokens\nGude Broz Co.. 1212 F St N W\nDEATHS\nMary Greenlees. 13 years. 11l Mon\nroe St. N. E.\nAnnie T. Gill. 11 yearn. 1111 Ton\nst. a. a.\nCatherine Elisabeth North. M yearn\nNational Luthoraa Homa\nArthur Dulany Addison. Tt years,\niiei q' st n. w.\nMary King. T1 roam. Hemo for\nPartch. OT years. ill Sixth\nst a w.\nMargaret M. Ortllp. IT yearn 4111\nFourth Bt. N. W.\nAlice May Clayton. 11 yean. 111! G\nBt. N. W.\nJames Powers. 19 yearn on route to\nFreedmen's Hospital.\nFrancis John Phillips, 10 years. Ds\npartment of Lsbor.\nMargarst B. Buchanan. 51 years, 1701\nMassachusetts Ave. N. W.\nPaul R. Ehrler, It years, 701 St\nN. E.\nCharles I. Griffith. It years, lilt\nMadison St N. W.\nPeter Carragher. 10 years. Casualty\nHospital.\nJulian Rooha. 41 years. Emsrgoncy\nHospital.\nJohn Heitor. It years. Naval Hospital.\nJacqusline DuPuy. 11 years, 1111\nMintwood PI. N. W.\nMargaret Loveless. TO years, 11 Florida\nAve. N. W.\nWilliam H. DeSpeara. 1 years, 1114\nFour and One-Half St. 8. W.\nKatherine Ann Koenig. 1 month. Chil\ndren's Hospital.\nRobert Toliver, 10 yearn Galllnger\nHospital.\nBenjamin H. Lloyd, 40 years, 101\nFifteenth St N. E.\nJames E. Newton. It years, till\nConnecticut Ave. N. W.\nThomas. Williams, 14 months. Gai-\nUnger Hospital.\nMARRIAGE LICENSES\nElmer Johnson. It, and Eleanora Sim\nmons, It, The Rev. J. T. Harvey.\nJoseph R. Mackall. 24, and Grace E.\nWashington, 11. The Rev. W. L. Wash\nington.\nJohn Brown, 11, and Virginia Wells,\n25. The Rev. J. McK. Jones.\nHenry P. Rollins 37. and Rosa\nLewie. St The Rev. A. Willbanka.\nOtto O. Daniel, 16, Leesburg, Va.\nand Elva E. Myers, 31, Ryan. Va. The\nRev. A. F. Poore.\nMitchell Wilson. 13, Phoebus, Va..\nand Daisy Goodrich, 25, Petersburg, Va.\nThe Rev. J. H. Dunham.\nSamuel Ferguson, 34. and Mary A.\nMeeks, 19. The Rev. W. D. Battle.\nThomae P. Martini, 21. and Allee\nBehring, It. The Rev. J. H. Dunham.\nWalter R. Walton, 21, Glens. Va.,\nand Alice P. Sears 21, Pamp< Va.\nThe Rev. L. I. McDougle.\nJack Siegel. 24, Baltimore. Md. and\nCelia Zucker, 20. Baltimore, Md. The\nRev. C. Silverstone.\nSamuel W. Friedlander. 40, Baltimore\nMd., and Irene 8. Rosenberg, 21, Balti\nmore, Md. The Rev. Aaron Volkman.\nJohn A. Smith, 24, and Mabie V.\nWhite. 21. The Rev. C. T. Murry.\nHenry Walder, 21, and Sarah Saks\n20. The Rev. S. H. Mots.\nClarence Wesley, 21, and Bernice\nBush,\" 11. The Rev. P. V. Grueheart.\nSamuel Ford. 34, aad Jeannette V\nEmmert, It. The Rev. A. F. Poore.\nLloyd B. Simpson, 44, and Marjorie\nE. Fentress 3\u00bb. The Rev. Earle Wilf,\nley.\nEdward P. Roberts 26, and Josephine\nA. Baucom, It. The Rev. E. H. Swem.\nJohn J. Ward, 3t, and 3. Pauline\nCollins. 32. The Rev. A. F. Poore.\nMitchell Stein, 27, and Irma Cohn.\n25. The Rev. S. H. Mets.\nNEARLY 4,000,000 IDLE\nBERLIN, Dec. 24 (I NJ3.) .\u2014Ger\nmany\u2019s unemployment problem\nwas growing by leaps and bounds\nas official figures published by\nthe government showed the num\nber of idle to be only 13,000\nshort of 4,000,000.\nChristmas Dinner\n11, sp. a.\nTwo Dillin--No Tipping\nChrlrtam Fruit Cu,\nBlue Paiat Cccktall\nCcawnaM R*yal,\nChsosa Toast\nBH\u00abW Sweet Dili* Heart, cf Celery\nPlaHcate Oliver\nReact Turkey\u2014ChMtaat Orcetla,\nGlblet Gravy\nCraabcrry Sauce ar Craabcrry Fra**,\nHet Mulled Cider\nCHOICE OF THREE\nWhipped Petatcee Sweet Petate Stall**\nNaw Fleel da Paa, Baked B*aaieh Oalen,\nHubbard Squath PaffTeaiate Filled Pe*,er\nCO* Slaw\nDlnaer Relle\nHeart, es Letuee\u2014 Krl, Krlafle Breccia*\nHellday Saadwleh\nCHOICE OF ol<E\nOld Eafllih Pluta Puddle, a la Mede\ner with Hard Sauce\nFrazee Em Ncm\u2014 Heel Ceekle,\nHet Miaee Pie\u2014Philadelphia Cream Cheece\nFreeh Strawberry lee Creaan-Fr