riation of $95,780 is available\nfor the addition.\nSix Ships to Carry\nRotarians Abroad\nNEW YORK, Dec. 24.\u2014Plans\nto provide transportation for\nabout 2,000 members of Rotary\nInternational, their families and\nguests, to the 1931 world conven\ntion at Vienna June 22 to 26 were\ndiscussed by the transportation\ncommittee at the Hotel Commo\ndore.\nDefinite bookings were placed\nfor about 1,000, while additional\nspace will be provided in the\nfleet of six ships that will sail\nfrom New York and Montreal be\ntween June 3 and 10.\nCanada Gives SI,OOO\nTo Flier for Rescue\nVANCOUVER, B. C., Dec. 24\n(I.NJS.).\u2014The Canadian govern\nment recognized the bravery of\nW. E. Wasson, Whitehorse, Yukon,\naviator, today when they granted\nthe pilot a SI,OOO gratuity for the\nrescue of Emil Kading, mechanic,\nand Bob (\u201cThree Finger\u201d) Marten,\nprospector, lost for two months in\nnorthern British Columbia.\nPartridge Named\nGreen\u2019s Successor\nVt., Dec. 24\n(UJB.).\u2014Frank C. Partridge, 69,\nformer United States minister to\nVenezuela, was yesterday named\nby Governor Weeks to fill the un\nexpired term in the United States\nSenate of Frank L. Green, the\nState\u2019s senior Senator, who died\nlast week.\n\u25a0WHEN YULETIDE\n\nLIGHTS SHINING\nWD/\n|>aot. A Merry\nChristmas too, to\nthose whom it\nwill be our privi\nlege to serve\nthe future. But,\nchiefly, a Merry,\nMerry Christmas\nto all, wherever\nthey may be, who\nshare with us the\njoy of this glad\nseason\u2014who feel\nfound pleasure with us again the\nand profit in deal- thrill that comes\ning with us in the but once a year.\nRinaldi (osl Co\n649 Rhode Island Avenue N. E.\nBranch Office, 2145 Georgia Ave. N. W.\nNorth 1600\nTHAT BETTER PENNSYLVANIA HARD COAL\nRomping\nAround\nRadio\nDial\nThe English Singers, of Lon\ndon, internationally famous\nchoral group, win be featured dur*\ning a program which wUi be\nbroadcast over \u2018an NB.C. net\nwork tonight at 10:30 p. m.\nThe six singers from London\nare specialists in choral work\nand have sung pinch on the\nContinent as well as in England.\nThey have made several tours of\nAmerica and the Fat East, and\nhave adopted the unusual custom\nof singing seated at ease around\na table.\nTheir programs are made up of\nmusical selections from the Six\nteenth Century, which many be\nlieve to be the golden age of\nEnglish music. The program\nconsists of madrigals, canzonets,\nballets and motets. The organi\nzation was brought to the United\nStates in 1925 by Mrs. Elizabeth\nSprague Coolidge to inaugurtae\nthe chamber music hall at the\nLibrary of Congress.\nThe singers Include Flora\nMann, Nellie Carson, Lillian\nBerger, Cuthbert Kelly, Norman\nStone and Norman Notley.\nRadio listeners in Seattle, Wash.,\nwill hear three of its native sons\non Christmas Eve in a broadcast\nover Station WOL, in Washing\nton, if nothing goes amiss.\nRon and Don, Fox Theater or\nganists, and Tom Olsen, thrir an\nnouncer, all hall from the Queen\nCity of the Charmed Land, and\nthey win be heard in an experi\nmental broadcast over the power\nful Capital City station from 3\nto 4 a. m\u201e Eastern standard\ntime, December 25, or from 12\nmidnight to 1 a. m., Christmas\nEve, in Seattle.\nThe broadcast will be by remote\ncontrol from the Fox Theater,\nand an appeal will be made for\nlisteners all over the North\nAmerican continent to report\ntheir reception.\nRon (Rinaldo Baggott) and\nDon (Donovan Moore), the popu\nlar Fox organ team, along with\nOlsen, attended the University of\nWashington at Seattle.\nThe Detroit Symphony Orches\ntra of 88 pieces and the Detroit\nSymphony Choir of 250 mixed\nvoices will join in a splendid con\ntribution to the nation\u2019s obser\nvance of Christinas Eve tonight\nwhen, from 10 to 11 p. m., over\nWMAL and associated stations of\nthe Columbia chain, they present\nthe Christmas music portion of\nHandel\u2019s famous oratorio,\n\u201cMessiah.\u201d\nThe group, which will conclude\nthe program, will open with